	  <title>Linear Equations with Infinitely Many Solutions</title>
	  <caption>Linear Equations with Infinitely Many Solutions</caption>
	  <showme>
		    <statement.showme>
			      <para>
            <para.body>If a system of linear equations has more than one solution, it automatically has infinitely many such. This is so because the solution hyperplanes of its equations intersect in a line or a plane or in a higher dimensional space.</para.body>
         </para>
			
			      <para>
            <para.body>
               <media type="image" active="0" inline="0">
                  <img src="ims/TwoEqnsR3NonParallel.gif"/>
               </media>
            </para.body>
         </para>
			
			      <para>
            <para.body>The RREF of a system of linear equations indicates that the system has infinitely many solutions as follows: there are
				<subordinate>
                  <hot>free variables</hot>
                  <info>
                     <para>
                        <para.body>A variable is called free if it is not tied to a leading <math>
                              <latex>1</latex>
                           </math>.</para.body>
                     </para>
                  </info>
               </subordinate>
				and the augmented part does not contain a leading <math>
                  <latex>1</latex>
               </math>.</para.body>
         </para>
			
			      <math.display>
				        <latex>
					
\begin{array}{ccccccccccccccc|c}
0 &amp; \cdots &amp; 0 &amp; 1 &amp; * &amp; \cdots &amp; * &amp; 0 &amp; * &amp; \cdots &amp; * &amp; 0 &amp; * &amp; \cdots &amp; * &amp; d_1 \\
0 &amp; \cdots &amp; 0 &amp; 0 &amp; 0 &amp; \cdots &amp; 0 &amp; 1 &amp; * &amp; \cdots &amp; * &amp; 0 &amp; * &amp; \cdots &amp; * &amp; d_2 \\
\vdots &amp;   &amp;   &amp; \vdots &amp; &amp;     &amp;   &amp; \vdots &amp; &amp;     &amp;   &amp; \vdots &amp; &amp;     &amp; \vdots &amp; \vdots \\
\vdots &amp;   &amp;   &amp; \vdots &amp; &amp;     &amp;   &amp; \vdots &amp; &amp;     &amp;   &amp; \vdots &amp; &amp;     &amp; \vdots &amp; \vdots \\
0 &amp; \cdots &amp; 0 &amp; 0 &amp; 0 &amp; \cdots &amp; 0 &amp; 0 &amp; 0 &amp; \cdots &amp; 0 &amp; 1 &amp; * &amp; \cdots &amp; * &amp; d_r \\
0 &amp; \cdots &amp; 0 &amp; 0 &amp; 0 &amp; \cdots &amp; 0 &amp; 0 &amp; 0 &amp; \cdots &amp; 0 &amp; 0 &amp; 0 &amp; \cdots &amp; 0 &amp; 0 \\
\vdots &amp;   &amp;   &amp; \vdots &amp; &amp;     &amp;   &amp; \vdots &amp; &amp;     &amp;   &amp; \vdots &amp; &amp;     &amp; \vdots &amp; \vdots \\
0 &amp; \cdots &amp; 0 &amp; 0 &amp; 0 &amp; \cdots &amp; 0 &amp; 0 &amp; 0 &amp; \cdots &amp; 0 &amp; 0 &amp; 0 &amp; \cdots &amp; 0 &amp; 0
\end{array}
					
				</latex>
			      </math.display>
			
			      <para>
            <para.body>Each column in the non-augmented part without a leading <math>
                  <latex>1</latex>
               </math> corresponds to a variable whose number values can be chosen freely. So there are infinitely many solutions. Visibly,</para.body>
         </para>
			
			      <para align="center">
            <para.body>(number of free variables) = (number of variables) - 
				<subordinate>
                  <hot>rank(system)</hot>
                  <info>
                     <para>
                        <para.body>The rank of a system of linear equations is the number of leading <math>
                              <latex>1</latex>
                           </math>â€™s in the RREF of its coefficient matrix.</para.body>
                     </para>
                  </info>
               </subordinate>
			         </para.body>
         </para>
